{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>It is really common to use maximum likelihood estimator (MLE) in machine learning. But do you ever think about the reason? Apart from the fact that it is prevalent and simple, here is why MLE is a very nice estimator.</p>\n<h2>Mean Square Error</h2>\n<p>Before discussing whether MLE is a good estimator, we need to come up with a criteria. And one of the most popular measure of a estimator is the mean square error (MSE). Here is the definition of MSE:</p>\n<span class=\"katex-display\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>E</mi><mo>(</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>[</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>−</mo><mi>θ</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>]</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>t</mi><mi>r</mi><mrow><mi>E</mi><mo>[</mo><mo>[</mo><mo>(</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>−</mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>(</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>−</mo><mi>θ</mi><msup><mo>)</mo><mi>T</mi></msup><mo>]</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">MSE(\\hat\\theta)=E[||\\hat\\theta-\\theta||_2^2]=tr{E[[(\\hat\\theta-\\theta)(\\hat\\theta-\\theta)^T]}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.2078799999999998em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord accent\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9578